Last week Jackson had an eye appointment to check for glaucoma. Due to the steroids he's been on for so long developing glaucoma is a concern. I'm happy to report he does not have glaucoma, however the Dr did say he has a thin pinpoint cataract developing on his right eye. Nothing to address but something to watch.

Jackson's Tacro is now with goal again as well. He's down to once a week physical therapy and no appointments until the end of May. Life is slowing down and we are enjoying it the best we can.

Hope you all are out and enjoying this beautiful April day! Today we let Jackson hop on his 4 wheeler for the first time and like the cautious kid he is he is taking it very slow. The kids are also trying to teach Henry their 5lb Chihuahua to ride 🤭

I've also had lots of messages lately regarding our journey and any advice I can give.

The most I can give is be your or your child's advocate and
👇
Take one Breath
One step
One day at a time

School has started back into session. Mae returned to public school while Jackson homeschools and Mae already has caught her first illness. Something we knew was going to happen but we were praying for wellness to surround her. 

In order to keep Jackson well we set Mae up to stay with MeMaw and PopT to reduce exposure.  Talk about a gut punch as a mother. Your youngest gets sick so you send her off. I felt sick doing that but it was the solution we came up with. Of course Mae handled it with stride and sadness. She wants to be home. Grandparents house isn't for you to feel yuck in🥺. I feel though having my mom so close helps but I hate that I couldn't care for both my kids in this situation. Her fever has broke and all test are negative, she just has a virus that has to run it's course. Tomorrow she can return to school.

We're going to have to do some thinking for the next time someone gets sick. There has to be a better way that doesn't make me feel this way.

But here is Jackson practicing his aim because he can't do anything with sister and now life for the moment is "soo boring". They truly love each other beyond anyone's imagination.  That brings me joy😊

School days are much easier now that we're in a routine. We wake up and take Mae to school, come home and walk Missy, eat breakfast and take medicine. After meds we start our school day. Today Kimber wanted to join in on learning fraction halves. We're fast approaching our 1 year transplant anniversary. But first we get to celebrate sisters BIRTHDAY!  The past two birthdays of Mae's Jackson was in the hospital. So this year we get to be home! We're all so excited to celebrate Mae's 7th birthday on the 24th 🎂

A year ago this wasn't possible. He was fighting for his life. 
.
.
.
.
A year ago a machine kept him alive and because of the love of another family he can be free from the constraints of a 200lb mechanical heart.  Yesterday they picked this Crepe Myrtle bouquet for me. My heart is full and oh so blessed for these little moments.  They had been bickering about something pretty so I told them to dance with each other and that's when it hit me again of how blessed we are.

Today was Mae's 7th birthday! It was so nice. We started the day with chocolate chip pancakes with Nutella and syrup. We then went out to the deer lease and hung out at the river for a little while. We drove around and checked out Poppa T's stand. Around lunch time we headed out and stopped for some burgers. Then we came home. Paw paw came by and MeMaw and Poppa T came over to give her their gifts. Aunt Peggy came over and others called to sing her happy birthday. It was a nice day. She got to pick all the meals and the day's activities. Happy

This morning I asked Jackson "How does it feel?" I could tell by his puzzled "About what?" Reply that he didn't realize the significance of this day. October 1st. Granted, I asked him as he was shuffling from his room and still waking up. 

I said "How does it feel, you've had your new heart for 1 year today?"

"Weird, I didn't think I was ever going to get a heart."

Not the statement I was expecting. It made my mind pause for a bit. I had to let that soak in. While we were at the hospital waiting we had lots of conversations about what if a heart wasn't gifted to him.

We are one of the blessed families that has made it to the other side of the transplant process. We were blessed to be offered a heart in time. A mighty strong and blessed heart.  This heart is strong enough to live through it's donor's trauma and death, survive through the transfer, survive through implantation into Jackson, the trauma of Jackson's recovery and is still going strong. 

Jackson continues to thrive. Yes he still has his battles, but he continues to be strong enough to work through them.

Strangers see him as a normal kid but we all know he is more than that. He's a living blessing because of a Super Hero🙏🙏🙏

🫶💪 Happy 1st of many Heartiversary's 💪🫶

Yup my son you ARE the definition of a fighter! Look how far you've come!

Those that haven't followed our story the first clip of Jackson is when he was placed on his mechanical heart the Berlin Heart on October 8th 2021. A 200+ pound machine that followed him everywhere. It became Jackson's heart for the next 358 days until a superheroes heart was placed Oct 1st 2022. Now 1 year later and he's beat the odds and preparing for his first livestock show! Something he's wanted to do since he was able to express things. We weren't sure if livestock showing would be possible after transplant but we're doing it with the blessing of his team and they are excited for him as well. 

Go JACKSON and MISSY!

It's getting close! The Trinity Valley Exposition, Inc. livestock show is next week, October 13-21. Jackson is taking his first pig Missy and his show is Oct 17th at 6pm with the auction on Friday the 20th. So you all know me and we had to mark this big occation with photos!
Ya'll we are so proud of this kiddo! He's worked so hard to get to where he is today. He just astonishes everyone at what is possible. Just one breath, one step, one day at a time.

What a relaxing week after a busy show week. I have to admit I really enjoyed the hustle of show week. I even noticed this week an increase of activity from Jackson from all his hustle show week as well.  We had a week of regrouping and relaxing but this weekend it was time to head to the pig sale.  There was a lot of cuties up there and we found a few we really liked but so did a lot of other people 🫤. This pig sale was an auction style and we were quickly outbidded on our top 5 pigs.  No don't get me wrong, this girl is still a nice pig and she's got all the right stuff to get Jackson in the show ring. She just wasn't our first choice.

After all the excitement of the auction we headed home with our piggy and got her all settled in just in time for a cold front 😊. She's a pretty sociable pig and the nice thing is she isn't a biter like Missy was. 

Jackson and Mae both spent hours this afternoon in the pen with her and loving on her. They let me pick her name on the way home. I was channeling my inner child to come up with a cool name. At first I picked Mustard but the eye rolls were felt from the backseat. So I said ok ok ok.....what about Honey Mustard and we call her Honey? Of course Jackson loved the name now because that's his favorite condiment! 😂🤷🏼‍♀️. Jackson's next show is the day after his 10th birthday!

Today they asked to go play and so we did. We headed out to the playground and they ran around for over an hour! I could tell Jackson was getting tired and so I asked him to take a 3-5 min sitting break and he protested. So I had him check his heart rate from his watch and it said 132bpm and he realized that yeah I'll sit for a bit. He counted each second and hopped up "OKAY it's been 3 minutes and my HR is 78" and he ran back to play some more. These kids have my heart and soul. Today I also let them have full decorating control of the Christmas tree.  We didn't set it up last year because we were only home a few days before Christmas so the kids were super excited when I asked if they were ready to put it up🥰🎄

The goals of children 😊.
